		<title>Home - Bash Programming</title>
	</head>
	<body>
		<input type="checkbox" id="toggle-menu" hidden>
		<Header />
		<Aside />
		<main>
			<section class="home-section">
				<h1>Introduction</h1>
				<p>Welcome! This site shares practical notes, examples, and mini-guides for Bash programming so you can move faster in the terminal and automate tasks.</p>
				<h2>What is Bash?</h2>
				<p>Bash (<b>B</b>ourne <b>A</b>gain <b>SH</b>ell</b>) is a Unix shell and command language. You type commands; Bash runs them, lets you chain them together, and write scripts to repeat tasks reliably. Bash is a powerful tool that allows you to automate tasks and create scripts to perform complex operations.</p>
				<h2>Why learn Bash?</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Automate repetitive work (backups, builds, deployments).</li>
					<li>Glue tools together with pipes and redirection.</li>
					<li>Process text and files quickly.</li>
					<li>Script tasks for reproducible results on any Unix-like system.</li>
				</ul>
				<h2>How to use Bash?</h2>
				<p>Bash is a command-line shell: you type a command, press Enter, and Bash runs it. You can chain commands, pass options, and connect programs togetherâ€”all interactively.</p>
			</section>
			<section class="code-section">
				<h3>Example</h3>
				<p>The following commands will output the home directory, the current working directory, and a message. <span class="bash-term">pwd</span> stands for "<b>p</b>rint <b>w</b>orking <b>d</b>irectory" and <span class="bash-term">echo</span> is used to print a message.</p>
				<!-- Codecard for the echo $HOME, pwd, echo Hello, World! commands -->
				<CodeCard 
					command={['echo $HOME', 'pwd', 'echo Hello, World!']}
					output={['/home/User', '/home/User', 'Hello, World!']}
				/>
			</section>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
